-- 05-meta-cell-designer.cell (v0.2)
-- A Cell program that designs Cell programs. Programs that write programs.
--
-- Tests: § quotation as data, ⊢∘ evolution loop, oracle-gated design iteration,
--        proof-carrying computation (design + verify), ⊢⊢ spawner (accumulate),
--        wildcard deps, file-scope ⊨?, guard clauses, ⊢∘-managed aspirational oracles
--
-- v0.2 changes from R16:
--   - Added file-scope ⊨? recovery policy
--   - Wildcard deps (vuln-scan-*→field) now formally spec-compliant
--   - ⊢⊢ spawn-scanners: added explicit `accumulate` mode
--   - Added guard clause on critique (only runs if problems exist)
--   - given? on redesign for optional critique output (tolerates ⊥)
--   - Oracles on design-cells are ⊢∘-managed (aspirational, not hard gates)
--   - cell-spec yields expressed as ⊢= with valid expression language
--
-- Domain: "An automated code review system that checks for security
-- vulnerabilities, suggests fixes, and verifies the fixes don't break
-- existing tests."

⊨? on failure:
  retry with «oracle.failures» appended to prompt
  max 3 attempts
⊨? on exhaustion:
  error-value(⊥)

⊢ domain
  given description ≡ "An automated code review system that checks for security vulnerabilities, suggests fixes, and verifies the fixes don't break existing tests."
  yield description

  ⊨ description is a clear problem domain

⊢ cell-spec
  given spec-path ≡ "docs/design/cell-v0.2-spec.md"
  yield symbols, execution-model, patterns

  ⊢= symbols ← "⊢ (declare cell), ∴ (soft body), ⊢= (hard body), ⊨ (oracle), ⊨? (recovery), § (quotation), «» (interpolation), ≡ (binding), → (output access), ▸ (refinement), ⊢∘ (evolution), ⊢⊢ (spawner), ⊥ (bottom), given? (optional dep), where (guard clause)"

  ⊢= execution-model ← "eval-one via Kahn's algorithm: find cells with all givens bound and guards true, evaluate one, check oracles, freeze yields. Monotonic — yields only get bound. Document IS the state. Guards skip cells cleanly (yields → ⊥). given? tolerates ⊥."

  ⊢= patterns ← "proof-carrying computation (LLM finds, code verifies), self-crystallization (∴ → ⊢=), evolution loops (⊢∘ rewrites soft cells), spawners (⊢⊢ grows frontier, accumulate or replace), cell-as-agent (inbox → dispatch → act), guard-based dispatch (given x where cond)"

⊢ decompose
  given domain→description
  yield components[], dataflow[]

  ∴ Analyze «domain→description» and decompose it into logical components
    for a Cell program. Identify:
    - What inputs the system needs (code diffs, test suites)
    - What processing stages are required (parse, scan, analyze, fix, verify)
    - What outputs the system produces (vulnerability reports, fix suggestions, test results)
    - How data flows between stages (which stage needs which outputs)

    Produce a components list (named processing stages) and a dataflow list
    (pairs of component→output connections).

  ⊨ length(components) ≥ 4
  ⊨ each component has a clear single responsibility
  ⊨ dataflow forms a DAG (no cycles)
  ⊨ dataflow covers every component (no orphans)

⊢ design-cells
  given decompose→components
  given decompose→dataflow
  given cell-spec→symbols
  given cell-spec→execution-model
  yield §program

  ∴ Using the Cell language symbols («cell-spec→symbols») and execution model
    («cell-spec→execution-model»), translate the components
    «decompose→components» and dataflow «decompose→dataflow» into a valid
    Cell program. For each component, write a ⊢ cell declaration with:
    - given: inputs from upstream cells (using → notation per dataflow)
    - yield: named outputs
    - ∴: natural language instruction for what the cell does
    - ⊨: oracle assertions that verify correctness

    Use ⊢= for any cell that can be deterministic (e.g., parsing, formatting).
    Use § quotation for cells that inspect other cells' definitions.
    Include at least one ⊢⊢ spawner if the domain requires parallel work
    (e.g., scanning multiple vulnerability categories independently).
    Use guard clauses (given x where condition) for conditional dispatch.

  ⊨ §program contains only valid Cell syntax
  ⊨ every component from decompose→components has a corresponding ⊢ cell
  ⊨ every dataflow edge from decompose→dataflow is expressed via given/→
  ⊨ at least one cell uses ⊢= (crystallized)
  ⊨ at least one cell has ⊨ oracles

⊢ trace-readiness
  given §program
  yield ready-order[], blocking-map

  ∴ Simulate eval-one scheduling on «§program». Walk the cell graph:
    1. Find cells with all givens already bound (≡ present) and guards true — these are ready
    2. Record which cells are blocked and what they wait for
    3. Determine the evaluation order (topological sort via Kahn's)
    4. Verify no cell is permanently blocked (all paths eventually resolve)
    5. For cells with guard clauses, note which guards could yield ⊥

    Output the ready-order (sequence of cell names in execution order) and
    a blocking-map (for each blocked cell, what it waits on).

  ⊨ ready-order is a valid topological sort of the cell graph
  ⊨ every cell in §program appears exactly once in ready-order
  ⊨ no cell is permanently blocked (all givens are eventually satisfiable)

⊢ simulate-oracles
  given §program
  given trace-readiness→ready-order
  yield oracle-results[], awkward-spots[]

  ∴ For each cell in «§program», evaluate its ⊨ oracle assertions:
    - Can the oracle be checked deterministically? (structural/value check)
    - Does it require LLM judgment? (semantic check)
    - Is the oracle too vague to be useful? (ambiguous)
    - Is the oracle redundant with the ∴ body? (tautological)

    Mark each oracle as: deterministic, semantic, ambiguous, or tautological.
    Collect awkward-spots: cells with ambiguous/tautological oracles, cells
    with no oracles, cells whose ∴ body is unclear or underspecified.

  ⊨ oracle-results covers every ⊨ in §program
  ⊨ each oracle-result classifies the oracle type
  ⊨ awkward-spots identifies genuine design weaknesses

⊢ critique
  given §program
  given simulate-oracles→awkward-spots where len(awkward-spots) > 0
  given trace-readiness→blocking-map
  yield problems[], suggestions[]

  ∴ Review «§program» for design problems:
    1. Awkward oracle spots: «simulate-oracles→awkward-spots»
    2. Missing edges: are there components that should connect but don't?
    3. Crystallization opportunities: which ∴ cells could be ⊢= instead?
    4. Missing spawners: does the domain need parallel processing not captured?
    5. Over-specification: are any ∴ blocks so detailed they're pseudocode?
    6. Under-specification: are any ∴ blocks too vague to execute?
    7. Missing guards: are there conditional branches without where clauses?

    For each problem, suggest a specific fix.

  ⊨ length(problems) ≥ 1
  ⊨ each problem has a corresponding suggestion
  ⊨ suggestions are actionable Cell syntax changes

⊢ redesign
  given §program
  given? critique→problems
  given? critique→suggestions
  yield §program'

  ∴ If «critique→problems» is ⊥ (no critique because no awkward spots were
    found), return «§program» unchanged.
    Otherwise, apply the suggestions «critique→suggestions» to fix the
    problems «critique→problems» in «§program». Rewrite affected cells.
    Preserve the overall structure — only change what needs fixing. Ensure
    the redesigned program still covers the full domain.

  ⊨ §program' has same top-level cell names as «§program» (unless cells were split/merged per suggestions)
  ⊨ if critique→problems is not ⊥ then every problem is addressed in §program'
  ⊨ §program' contains only valid Cell syntax

⊢∘ evolve(design-cells, decompose→components, decompose→dataflow, cell-spec→symbols, cell-spec→execution-model)
  through critique, redesign
  until len(critique→problems) = 0 or critique→problems = ⊥
  max 3

  -- Each iteration: design-cells produces §program → trace-readiness
  -- checks scheduling → simulate-oracles checks oracle quality →
  -- critique finds problems (guard: only if awkward-spots exist) →
  -- redesign fixes them → redesigned §program' replaces design-cells output.
  -- Interface frozen, implementation evolves.
  --
  -- design-cells oracles are aspirational under ⊢∘ management: they describe
  -- ideal program quality but don't independently block freezing. The ⊢∘
  -- until condition (no remaining problems) is the actual convergence gate.

⊢ emit-program
  given redesign→§program'
  given domain→description
  yield final-cell-file

  ∴ Format «redesign→§program'» as a complete .cell file with:
    - Header comment describing the domain: «domain→description»
    - All cell declarations from the program
    - Clean formatting following Cell conventions
    - File-scope ⊨? recovery policy

    This is the ready-to-run output.

  ⊨ final-cell-file is valid Cell syntax
  ⊨ final-cell-file has a descriptive header comment
  ⊨ final-cell-file addresses the complete domain description
